commit_message:
Add in further token validation in v3_auth tests

Add in extra unscoped token validation tests that verify that the
validate of the token is infact issuing a 404. These additions
were originally part of the Fernet testing changes, but were
extracted to stand on their own as they are adding further test
functionality that is not directly applicable to fernet.

Co-Authored-By: Samuel de Medeiros Queiroz <samuel@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: I683f988f6ff3e5e3f5acc5e8565403f72127c88f

commit_message:
Make second level of Rabbit OCF monitor only at slaves

W/o this fix, monitor check level 30 is not always
added into the CIB for RabbitMQ pacemaker resource.

The w/a is to define second monitor only for slaves.

Closes-bug: #1462899

Change-Id: I678b4af19e846a2a7f6c4ce829a1a8b5a4391876
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fix agents update parameter name

According to Ken'ichi Ohmichi's TODO comment,
The parameter in nova/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/agents.py
function: update, name "para" is different from the ones of the
other APIs. Most other names are resource names like "server" etc.
This name should be changed to "agent" for consistent naming.

Change-Id: Ib0125d3c3079a772337d240a5414860de3d1ca3e
Closes-Bug:1458286

oslo.config makes attempts to autodiscover configuration files using
find_config_files() helper. If e.g. /etc/neutron/neutron.conf exists,
and is not readable, the following test failure can be experienced:

oslo_config.cfg.ConfigFilesPermissionDeniedError: Failed to open some
config files: /etc/neutron/neutron.conf

Unit tests must not rely on any external state of the system and run
successfully no matter whether neutron is actually installed on the
system, or not.

Closes-Bug: #1442543
Change-Id: Ic90d8c40b2072fdda152703b84081719936b5f4e
(cherry picked from commit 54fc39308277d4aedc3e399286714d719ecacfbb)
"}]
commit_message:
tests: don't allow oslo.config to autodiscover config files

oslo.config makes attempts to autodiscover configuration files using
find_config_files() helper. If e.g. /etc/neutron/neutron.conf exists,
and is not readable, the following test failure can be experienced:

oslo_config.cfg.ConfigFilesPermissionDeniedError: Failed to open some
config files: /etc/neutron/neutron.conf

Unit tests must not rely on any external state of the system and run
successfully no matter whether neutron is actually installed on the
system, or not.

Closes-Bug: #1442543
Change-Id: Ic90d8c40b2072fdda152703b84081719936b5f4e
(cherry picked from commit 54fc39308277d4aedc3e399286714d719ecacfbb)

commit_message:
Adding Publisher Acknowledgements/confirms

During the vancouver summit, Michael Klishin from
pivotal proposed we should use publisher confirms
as the default setting to reduce messages being
dropped on the floor.

https://www.rabbitmq.com/confirms.html
http://www.rabbitmq.com/blog/2011/02/10/introducing-publisher-confirms/

This setting is a lightweight way of keeping track of which messages
have been processed by the broker and which would need re-publishing
in case of broker shutdown or network failure.

Change-Id: I25bc955df130dad4725f5281211d37fd73e7ea63

commit_message:
Allow override of os-brick library used by cinder

os-brick code was pulled out of cinder and made into its own library
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/155552/

added to requirements:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/177372/

Integration tests were added
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/188156/

But they still use the version of os-brick from pip.

This change updates devstack to pull in the changes from
os-brick patch sets instead, when configured to do so.

Needed-by: Id2bc10782847861fe4bb5e9e46245654450e38fd

Change-Id: I5359dd37dfe94bd469d5ca35f9fbaeda61b5fac4

commit_message:
Add default_client_name in Nova::FloatingIPAssoc

default_client_name has been missed, so stack fails
to delete, if server, from which floating ip association
depends, not exist.

Change-Id: I01bb91f8afaeb483e1a4bb55653dc3189a62bf12
Closes-bug: #1396982
(cherry picked from commit 898f94347dc011aba7f2cb03b1ff5d384691aeda)

commit_message:
Convert SyncPoint.entity_id from String to Integer

The sync point entity id is a string field currently that can take
either the value of a stack.id or a resource.id. Now that stack.id
and resource.id are both integers, change the field type to Integer
too.

Change-Id: I846d3b483a964e14450b67d59321dcdf50817111

commit_message:
docs: fixup libvirt NUMA testing docs to match reality

The libvirt NUMA testing docs were written before the final code
was merged, so the example JSON shown for the database fields
did not match reality. It was also hard to read the JSON since
there were no line breaks & indentation. To make matters even
worse, the final example was just plain wrong - the data shown
was a mixture of a guest with 1 NUMA node and a guest with 2
NUMA nodes.

Change-Id: I51e4df2d9fe252ba65f6a37d84f125e18b44e239

commit_message:
Add running functional scripts for defined backend

This CR allows running "functional" tox job for different backends.
Short description about expected workflow:
1. Gate job run ceilometer/ceilometer/tests/functional/hooks/post_test_hook.py
with <backend> parameter.
2. This script run "tox -efunctional" command with defined variable
CEILOMETER_TEST_BACKEND
3. After in "run-functional-tests.sh" setup script for the backend
and testr are runned.

In this CR running testr with pretty_tox.sh script added because
it allows to use subunit-trace output which developed in tempest-lib
and improve useful of testr output.

Partially implements: blueprint ceilometer-functional-tests
Change-Id: Idb66aca0b46779516db2baec856df8223dbe5c13

commit_message:
Add testcases to test DefaultDomain

As to the external authentication methods, we have `KerberosDomain`, `Domain`
and `DefaultDomain` defined, `DefaultDomain` is a different usecase compared
with `KerberosDomain` and `Domain`.

We have testcases for `KerberosDomain` and `Domain`, but there is no testcase
to verify `DefaultDomain`, so we need to fix it up.

Change-Id: Iec3e9a44c0b6fa22305aaf05f2f2aa9bffbf7b49
Closes-Bug: #1459116

commit_message:
tenant-list updated to output Tenant Description

Updated the keystone tenant-list command to be able to display the
tenant  description. The description will be included only when --show-
description option is set to true.

Co-Authored-By: Yamini Sardana <yamini.sardana@tcs.com>
Co-Authored-By: Kamil Rykowski <kamil.rykowski@intel.com>

Change-Id: I8ef317e8be7bd8f35a83039ea280ac43fc48d74f
Closes-bug: #1398723

Copy worlddump output if it exists

We call worlddump in devtack, but aren't collecting it (it is collected
in grenade though).

commit_message:
Fix "Quick Deploy" crash after re-login

Now error occurred when user presses "Quick Deploy" 
with expired token. After logging in, murano dashboard crashes. 

Also, the same behavior is seen when user tries to click "Quick Deploy"
 form on the separate window or page is expired.
 This fix allows to show requested form.

What is not are going to be fixed:
* Form became unmodal if opened in a separate window, like every other
  horizon form since all java script, that makes form modal remained on
  the previous page

* If form contained plus for dependency form creation - link won't work,
 since there is no required javascript code on a new page.

Change-Id: I44011a2d575303b93f3ce430fe1aeede971dbd99
Closes-Bug: #1397972

commit_message:
Fixed keystone user-role-list command error issue

While using token authentication, the user-role-list command is not able to get user-id and tenant-id with existing implementation.In the fix thease values are obtained using os_username and os_tenant_name.

Change-Id: I375f4a60f945c8d01f3cdb9d80d2a6c51c00fb26
Fixes: bug #1436445

commit_message:
Fixed keystone user-role-list command error issue

While using token authentication, the user-role-list command is not able to get the user and tenant details. When this command is used without passing user and tenant details, an error message is displayed.

Change-Id: I149b7e2a8561affe6d434538a921f8eff78fad89
Fixes: bug #1436445

commit_message:
Cause gabbi to skip on no storage sooner

This avoids problems interacting with the global CONF used by
prepare_service that happen when the fixture is skipped. If we skip
before ever accessign the CONF we have a better known state.

This problem was discovered by comparing runs of the gabbi tests
with mongo and mysql (they only work with mongo, by design).

Change-Id: I9567fb0b37e68cd92f141697e4af8882c10a33f7

commit_message:
Create DHCP port for IPv6 subnet

There is a bug in dhcp agent code that when first port is created
in an IPv6 subnet, DHCP port is not automatically created.

This fix resolves this problem by removing the IP version check
in configure_dhcp_for_network method.

Change-Id: If3f405d367a7099d9f33d72d11ffcb7a393abe23
Closes-Bug: #1367500
(cherry picked from commit 1b66e11b5d8c0b3de0610ca02c3e10b6f64ae375)

commit_message:
IBP: accept removable block devices only from vendor list

fuel-agent should ignore removable block device if their vendor
isn't in approved vendor list.
It's a backport of what has been already implemented in
nailgun-agent.

Change-Id: I406eb4d9539f1be55f97dce73cf2f611941fabd4
Closes-Bug: #1462397

commit_message:
[stable/6.1]Fix find_host for non-vcenter deployment

After adding support of vcenter,
for tests where we check connectivity
by floating ip we start to ssh on compute if nova network is used. So this change start return controllers
ip in case if use_vcenter is false

Change-Id: I8952ee78e8b2b94a1998f57a59ae7fa33ddbf629
Closes-Bug: #1443893

commit_message:
Merge V2 and V2.1 cloudpipe functional tests

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges cloudpipe functional tests.

In V2 hypervsior API has following extensions
- os-cloudpipe
- os-cloudpipe-update

In V2.1 above extensions have been merged together in cloudpipe plugins

Change-Id: Idf76e584fc2ec9508d93edead48ffc90a8c25257

commit_message:
[IBP] Verify the filesystem after expanding it

Resizing filesystem is inherently dangerous operation and can fail
both due to hardware problems and software bugs. Therefore check the
filesystem after resizing it to prevent the greater damage.

While at it make sure Ubuntu FS images produced by fuel-agent can be
resized up to 8 TB.

Related-Bug: #1459665
Change-Id: Iefd4504a13a581309805b358900cb94c53f57e81

commit_message:
Disable py26 jos for glance_store

We've dropped support for py26 on glance_store Liberty. This patch
disables the jobs for the master branch and keeps it around, as a gate,
on stable/kilo.

Co-Authored-By: Ian Cordasco <ian.cordasco@rackspace.com>
Change-Id: I7b014a4cbe1ca3b6c177c695c23baa2e660c6374

commit_message:
VMware: remove unused parameter for VMOPS spawn

There is no longer a need for the power_on paremeter to be passed
tp the spawn opertaion. This was originally used for the rescue but
commit cd1765459a24e52e1b933c8e05517fed75ac9d41 ensured that we no
longer need this.

This patch remove a parameter that is no longer needed and cleans
up tests related to this.

TrivilaFix

Change-Id: If719b94cf50d5f2212eac4807c80edb886bf7808

commit_message:
Fix an objects layering violation in compute/api

This patch fixes a case in compute/api that "knows" the magic name for
where we store actual object contents.

I'm not sure about this actual use and why we need it, but in order to
not block subsequent patches, this makes it at least use the proper
API in order to generate the magic attribute name.

Related to blueprint use-oslo-objects

Change-Id: I4fa95f03106130c64b672c32247686d109c760f7

commit_message:
How to configure haproxy

This is a slightly edited version of the information in the old ha-guide,
based on the material in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/164998/.

This section needs more information to explain the sample file that is provided
and instructions for restarting HAProxy after modifying the file.

Also we wanted a mention of commercial load-balancers added to this section;
please provide appropriate wording.

commit_message:
Remove assertRemotes() from objects tests

When we started working on objects, we had some stuff in the tests to
ensure that remote calls were made when expected and not when not.
Almost all objects tests after the original push have not made those
assertions, and the ones that did never caught anything. The original
intent of those was to make sure we weren't cheating with local calls
ahead of breaking db access by nodes like compute. Since we're well
past that point now, and since we never really were consistent about
it, this patch removes it ahead of later patches to convert us to
oslo_versionedobjects, which won't record remote calls in the same
way anyway.

Related to blueprint use-oslo-objects

Change-Id: I9de7cf75a64b5d20ec9275a6efa31d8cba76b35f

commit_message:
Use fields from oslo.versionedobjects

This removes as many of our basic fields as possible, replacing them with
implementations from oslo.versionedobjects. Because the field classnames
have changed, each object hash needs to be updated, even though nothing has
really changed. It leaves the field tests in place to prove that fact. I will
remove them in a later patch.

Related to blueprint use-oslo-objects
Change-Id: Iab399fdd8425d423dba82f0ec98e754c51e62170

commit_message:
Convert test objects to new field formats

The test objects in test_objects were written before we had the auto-typing
field helpers. To ease the transition to oslo.versionedobjects, this patch
pre-converts them to the newer format.

Related to blueprint use-oslo-objects

Change-Id: I1db2ac498e1ebcebee7dc6dde404cc120782f705

commit_message:
Fix property validation for TemplateResource during update

This fix adds schema regeneration before props are validated
for TemplateResource during stack-update.

Change-Id: Ia79a25083489f48ed7332fbbd089a0090452cdc4
Closes-Bug: #1452983
Closes-Bug: #1453923
(cherry picked from commit 141597f032a38fdd96c97c14c0517db9463dd9c9)

commit_message:
Make heatclient-dsvm-functional check for heatcli

Now that heatclient-dsvm-functional is passing on experimental check
(I562c9d4d45ee4773d80b1ef0ceec6bb9af839a29) move functional testing to
check queues as non voting untill (I562c9d4d45ee4773d80b1ef0ceec6bb9af839a29)
is not merged.

commit_message:
Make Manila scenario testing voting

The scenario test run stable as non-voting job for some weeks.
Make it voting for check and gate.

Change-Id: Id6aa302c8d66da87addac24e9130d8cc8b018015

So for hypervisors controlled by nova-network with proxy-mode there will be no neutron agents running, only neutron server which will provide/save data for nova-network. Neutron agent will be started later, after hypervisor reboot, and at that moment it will do proper config on the hypervisor (e.g. security groups update). Not sure I got the question right or I may be missing something.'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2015-01-28 16:40:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I was referring to the membership update which is used for security groues with a rule for 'source security group'. If you have a network which spans across hypervisors managed by neutron agents and nova-network, and we spawn a vm on the nova-network side, there is an additional IP address of which neutron's l2 agents should be aware. I think also the opposite might be true - when you boot a vm on a neutron network there is an additional IP address in neutron for which an update on security groups on the nova network side is necessary.

Is this something that can be easily dealt with?"}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-01-29 14:12:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

ok, so currently I think that no special handling will be needed for the case of spawning a vm on nova-netwok hypervisor.
Most probably it is because I'm an optimist :)
The way I see this at the moment is:

  - nova-net creates proper nova-objects (vif, fip)
  - nova-net saves objects - this is where proxy does neutron API calls instead of db calls
  - nova-net configures network, security groups.. as usual
  - neutron receives request on port creation, creates it in db and notifies all the agents listening on neutron hypervisors

As for spawning a vm on neutron migrated hypervisor I guess we should add special hooks in neutron api at nova side,
such as calling nova's secgroup RPC API on port creation."}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-01-30 15:39:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-30 16:39:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

I'm pretty concerned about this approach for a couple of reasons.

First, we don't actually have the machinery in place to allow you to redefine an object like Network and have it be used instead of the SQLAlchemy object. Granted, that's the long-term plan for things like this, but we don't have it now.

Second, I'm not sure this is the correct layer at which to implement this proxy. A lot of this seems like duplicated work from the neutronapi, but at a lower level. I think that expecting to have the persistence layer replaced underneath nova-network and have it behave properly is likely to be fraught with issues.

Why do you think this is better that just converting to use neutronapi once neutron actually is the source of truth?"}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-02-09 08:31:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Thanks for the review Dan. Please see my replies below

>> First, we don't actually have the machinery in place to allow you to redefine an object 
>> like Network and have it be used instead of the SQLAlchemy object. Granted, that's the long-term 
>> plan for things like this, but we don't have it now.

Not sure I understand, actually this is what this patch is doing - redefines Network object and
make it be used instead of original object. What do you mean by SQLAlchemy object?

>> Second, I'm not sure this is the correct layer at which to implement this proxy. 
>> A lot of this seems like duplicated work from the neutronapi, but at a lower level.
>> I think that expecting to have the persistence layer replaced underneath nova-network and 
>> have it behave properly is likely to be fraught with issues.

I would be glad to find a way which would be less fraught with issues, so I'm open to suggestions.

>> Why do you think this is better that just converting to use neutronapi once neutron actually 
>> is the source of truth?

Switching to use neutronapi means we already migrated, no? IOW I think just converting to neutronapi 
will not work without hypervisor reboot (or "smart" live transition if available) - which is still 
in plan but at later stage [1].

Let's define what is nova-network proxy then and whether we need it at all. As I see, it's just
the same nova-network code with hooks at points where it gets/saves data to DB and those points are 
in objects. The main purpoise of the proxy is to be able to support nova-net and neutron hypervisors 
to coexist to provide a way for rolling upgrades.

[1]https://review.openstack.org/#/c/142456'}, {'account_id': 11279, 'date': '2015-02-10 09:46:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Dan: Unfortunately we can't just switch all the compute nodes over to neutron in some enormous atomic step - so the high-level migration process has a period where the neutron DB is the source of truth, but there is at least one compute node still running nova-network.

If you can suggest a less terrible place to have nova-api configure a nova-network compute node, but read the information from neutron DB then we're all ears ;)

In particular, if we move to a higher level I fear we'll just end up duplicating much of nova-network instead.  Do you think that would turn out to be less code than this current approach?"}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-02-12 21:10:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

Oleg, I just don't think that substituting a different network object underneath the normal nova-network code is the right place to do this, even if you had a non-hacky way to convince nova-network to use the redefined object, I don't think it's the right layer at which to switch things out.

Angus, I know that we can't make an atomic switchover. I feel like doing this at the nova/network/base_api.py layer is the proper place, probably subclassing the nova-net one and re-using a lot of what is there. I guess that I don't believe that just replacing the persistence layer is going to be enough to cover more than just the most simple of cases."}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-02-13 09:02:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Dan, I'd really like to understand your concerns a bit better. 
Replacing the persistence layer from nova to neutron db is all what we're trying to accomplish with the proxy. Why do you think it won't be enough? What are the cases that won't be covered?

Both nova-net api and manager are using nova-objects all over the place. So I'm afraid subclassing would mean a significant rewriting of nova-net code (developing/review nightmare!). The result will be some kind of hybrid which we can't really call nova-network.

What I like in proxying at objects layer is that nova-net code stays untouched and the changes are scoped to only mapping of data returned by neutron api to format that nova-net expects (and vice-versa)"}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-02-13 13:27:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-2

Sorry, this needs a nova blueprint to merge during kilo.'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-02-13 14:35:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I'm in agreement with Dan.  This is a bit more hacky than is comfortable for this transition.  It assumes that all relevant network operations will go through the Network object, which I'm not sure is true.  How does allocate_for_instance work in this case?

There is also the question of testing that was pointed out.  There will need to be something in place to ensure that the objects remain compatible.  Furthermore there would need to be some careful thought about remoting/backporting the object if that could happen and what the consequences would be."}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-02-13 15:20:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Andrew,

>> I'm in agreement with Dan. This is a bit more hacky than is comfortable for this transition. 

Honestly, I'll be more than happy to know a less hacky approach. Please see my previous comment on why I prefer current one.

>> It assumes that all relevant network operations will go through the Network object, which I'm not sure is true. How does allocate_for_instance work in this case?

not only Network object, but all networking-related objects. 
AFAIK nova-net does not talk to db directly but uses conductor through nova-objects. Thus if we properly redefine relevant objects we should be ok.

>> There is also the question of testing that was pointed out. There will need to be something in place to ensure that the objects remain compatible. Furthermore there would need to be some careful thought about remoting/backporting the object if that could happen and what the consequences would be.

Testing is definitely a must. Special "sideways" grenade job is planned for this (please see blueprint spec) - I believe it can also be used to test half-way migration where only db migration and proxy mode are tested.
Regarding objects compatibility - hacked objects are derived from original ones with hooks to store/fetch relevant info in neutron. Since we're moving to nova-net deprecation I don't expect many/significant changes to net objects. However if that happens I believe we can deal with it on case by case basis.'}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-02-16 10:29:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6316, 'date': '2015-02-17 10:19:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

So from the nova-net to neutron migration meeting, nova feels this direction is awkward. John Garbutt elucidated the position of subclassing the api as a direction, but admitted that nova is closed to new features in their cycle.

I proposed that we continue work aiming for L at this point, moving in the direction of creating the api subclasses. We will need nova core reviewer sponsors for the work. I will see about getting those. Once we have agreement on api subclasses as a direction we can figure out timing and submit specs and blueprints for L.

My understanding is that this direction will allow us to continue working though code won't be merged until L is open."}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-02-17 16:16:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-02-17 16:20:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-02-17 16:21:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Dan, Andrew, honestly, I'd really like to find more simple/reliable approach. My resistance here is not because I'm so proud of my "idea", I just can't see reasonable alternative.

AFAIU your proposal is to proxy at higher (api) level. First of all I think the best proxy at that level is existing neutron api which as we know we cannot switch to right after db migration.

I'm sure that subclassing nova-net api and manager to make them work with neutron will be much more painfully as they use nova objects quite heavily and expect data in certain formats. So eventually we will still need to go to lower level.
 
Let's take for example get network [1]: I'm not sure how it will be different/better to proxy at api level rather than at object level. Or create_networks [2] - do you guys think it's better/simpler/more reliable to proxy it at api layer than how it's done in current revision? Also need to account that neutron won't contain all needed info so we'll need to combine data from nova and neutron DBs. I couldn't force myself to try it to show how terrible it will look like.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/network/api.py#L97
[2] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/network/manager.py#L1226

You also had concerns on how current approach will cover more complex cases. Is allocate_for_instance complex enough? Can I convince you by covering it in next revisions?

Please help me understand your proposal better if I got it wrong somehow.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-17 17:25:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
WIP: adding neutron-proxy mode to nova running with nova-net

The idea is to override network-related objects so that they
use neutron REST API for getting/saving data rather then
using conductor/nova db. That should be only for data relevant
to neutron.
For those data fields that cannot be stored in neutron the proposal
is to continue using nova db: neutron does not need that data
and cannot change it so it should be safe.

It should be enough to properly redefine network-related objects'
methods for nova-net to work correctly using neutron as
source of truth.

WIP: need proxies for FloatingIP, SecurityGroups(? probably
can just switch to neutron sec-group api)

Patch in its current state supports network create/delete,
allocate/deallocate_for_instance in proxy mode.
It could be tested together with db data transition patch [1]
migrating data from nova db first, then enabling proxy mode 
and check everything still works fine

[1] https://review.openstack.org/148260/

Partially implements blueprint migration-from-nova-net

Change-Id: I682fc1432173d6c0e816fa3e6edca216243768ab

I wrote this patch to run nova tests with oslo.vmware 0.13.1... and tests failed, but I'm not sure that failures are related. Anyway, the change was merged in global requirements. I abandon this change. I will wait until the bot submit the usual patch to update nova requirements."}]

commit_message:
Fix cloud-init Python syntax for Python < 2.6

The loguserdata.py file gets uploaded to the servers created by Heat to run
under cloud-init. Since the default versions of Python installed on the
user's server may be very old (e.g. RHEL 5 defaults to Python 2.4), avoid
using the octal syntax introduced for Python 3.0 and backported only as far
as Python 2.6. (Also avoid the old syntax, which will break on Python 3.x.)

Also remove use of the "with" statement from loguserdata.py and
part-handler.py. This statement is only available from Python 2.6 on (or in
Python 2.5 via "from __future__ import with_statement").

Finally, remove use of the "except ExceptionType as value" syntax for
catching exceptions. Again, this was only backported to Python 2.6.

Change-Id: I89e86d00993d51e2514b1e589503c6d966909403
Partial-Bug: #1375864
(cherry picked from commit 95ec13c5725ccc19dfe910fe83eb9bc6799d482e)
(cherry picked from commit 140d66e587bce27523ee7ebbeaecbced83082949)

commit_message:
Add quotes to unsafe if conditions in mapr element

In some cases unsafe if conditions can produce errors. Quotes should be used
to avoid problems with empty variables

Change-Id: Ia977bfa570ff9c3703a1a2dd370e1be0bf1b7a85
Closes-bug: #1463144

commit_message:
Removed a non-conditional 'if' statement

In a recent refactor of the libvirt driver an 'if'
statement was left remaining which was no longer
conditional as the variable is now a constant.

This removes the exuberant 'if' statement.

Change-Id: Ie3545554859e2a0fc4b294f4f464dd9bdd9f93c5
Signed-off-by: Dave Walker (Daviey) <email@daviey.com>

commit_message:
stack_get of heat_v1 driver now accpet stack_id as input param

When invoking get_stack method of openstacksdk orchestration proxy,
stack_id should be transmitted as input parameter. This patch fixed
related bugs in both heat_v1 driver and heat stack profile.

Change-Id: Ic254236d925b91c50ee2b22e3d1392931eb18fb1

commit_message:
Add column "hidden" to volumes table

The default value of hidden is 0, which means it will be displayed
via the command cinder list. Otherwise it will not be desplayed via
cinder list.

Change-Id: I55364798e91fab7a5224fa5a4891f9a5d703aa4d
Partially-Implements: blueprint migration-improvement

if not specified in config.

commit_message:
fix the value of query_spec.maxSample to advoid to be zero

code before:
VC_REAL_TIME_SAMPLING_INTERVAL = 20

samples_cnt = (int(duration / VC_REAL_TIME_SAMPLING_INTERVAL)
if duration else 1)
query_spec.maxSample = samples_cnt

if we set the value of "interval" in /etc/ceilometer/pipline.yaml to less
than 20,the value of "query_spec.maxSample" will be 0,which will cause
problem when use it to send request to vsphere server

Change-Id: Ibdb586109fe5334f3080539a40ff92badead837b
Closes-Bug:#1415307
(cherry picked from commit 53fe9976cc48c3c301b74044bae6c23b8dbb1d63)

subject: fix the value of query_spec.maxSample to advoid to be zero

commit_message:
fix the value of query_spec.maxSample to advoid to be zero

code before:
VC_REAL_TIME_SAMPLING_INTERVAL = 20

samples_cnt = (int(duration / VC_REAL_TIME_SAMPLING_INTERVAL)
if duration else 1)
query_spec.maxSample = samples_cnt

if we set the value of "interval" in /etc/ceilometer/pipline.yaml to less
than 20,the value of "query_spec.maxSample" will be 0,which will cause
problem when use it to send request to vsphere server

Change-Id: Ibdb586109fe5334f3080539a40ff92badead837b
Closes-Bug:#1415307
(cherry picked from commit 53fe9976cc48c3c301b74044bae6c23b8dbb1d63)

commit_message:
Update templates regarding changes in horizon

* Application wizard template hasn't got a wizard_create template
* Templates and views were updated regarding changes in horizon
* Use horizon modal form template instead of customized one
* Fix padding at app wizard header

Closes-Bug: #1459221

commit_message:
Removes contrib entry from Designate spec

In Liberty summit, it was decided to keep the
designate resource plug-ins as part of heat main tree.
So, this patch removes the contrib entry from the
designate resource plugin spec

blueprint heat-designate-resource

Change-Id: I7a2f4dee648e23bd4b83e5b74875091824e81be8

commit_message:
Added test for DVR device owner check using port

Added test for Negative test to add subnet as interface
when port from same subnet exits as interface

Added test for dvr snat port creation with
device owner router centralized snat

commit_message:
Enable use of coordination_url in ceilometer

Since t-h-t can now deploy a Redis cluster, we can rely on it as the
tooz backend for high availability.

Change-Id: If045a273388aa2e725b6de624e09aa9c85248cc4

[{'created': '2015-06-01 07:57:55.000000000', 'message': "Enable 'Allowed Address Pairs' extension

This patch enables the allowed address pairs extension.
In concrete terms, it allows us to pass information on
the pairs of mac addresses and and ip addresses that we
don't have to filter out as a part of anti-spoofing. This
comes with the Port object sent over the the midonet backend.

The neutron extension itself is described at:
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1hyB3dIkRF623JlUsvtQFo9fCKLsy0gN8Jf6SWnqbWWA/edit

Change-Id: Ifee3cd0d7fed1dbb9dd32148253eb405d89cdccb
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>

commit_message:
Enable 'Allowed Address Pairs' extension

This patch enables the allowed address pairs extension.
In concrete terms, it allows us to pass information on
the pairs of mac addresses and ip addresses that we
don't have to filter out as a part of anti-spoofing. This
comes with the Port object sent over the midonet backend.

The neutron extension itself is described at:
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1hyB3dIkRF623JlUsvtQFo9fCKLsy0gN8Jf6SWnqbWWA/edit

Change-Id: Ifee3cd0d7fed1dbb9dd32148253eb405d89cdccb
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>

commit_message:
Share admin password func test between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges admin password functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled for v2.1 tests to run
successfully.

Change-Id: Icfb9253ffb0852d15e685045a31b9fe811722733

commit_message:
Merge fping functional tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges fping functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled tests to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.

Change-Id: I1dd91402c38736accea0e9b73be66a9aaa72c4f3

commit_message:
Share deferred_delete func tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges deferred delete functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.

Change-Id: Ice79473ec5640f87de659d32a094c321e4b1f0db

commit_message:
Merge server personality tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges servers personality functional tests.
Also inherit personality tests from ServersSampleBase to reuse code.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.

Note- V2 has no separate personality tests. This was added as separate
plugin in v2.1

Change-Id: I0e61ad236c0168977cad89432490f803eb3a61fd

commit_message:
Merge test_admin_actions between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges admin actions functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled for v2.1 tests to run
successfully.

Change-Id: I0b942e038ae6b50837e246f76c1e592539f1761a

commit_message:
Apply other "get" rule of GET to image v1 client

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the part
of the rule to image v1 client.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I3440765c3117ec4022c470429008caf0d7464935

commit_message:
LogABug: Publish URL of current page

Add the URL of the current page to the comment section when reporting a
bug. The clouddocs-maven-plugin did this and it is helpful to quickly
locate the page where the error was reported against.

Change-Id: Ia104739b7f4140c35d23c80c57ec52261268a1bf

commit_message:
set MIDO_DB_USER/MIDO_DB_PASSWORD in devstack

Devmido has MIDO_DB_USER and MIDO_DB_PASSWORD env variables to create
the connection string to MySQL. Set these variables from devstack.

Change-Id: Ia3c26a4fffb69e655ff987507fe7bc8eef844922
Implements: MNA-439

default_client_name has been missed, so stack fails

Change-Id: I01bb91f8afaeb483e1a4bb55653dc3189a62bf12
Closes-bug: #1396982
'}]
commit_message:
Add default_client_name in Nova::FloatingIPAssoc

default_client_name has been missed, so stack fails
to delete, if server, from which floating ip association
depends, not exist.

Change-Id: I01bb91f8afaeb483e1a4bb55653dc3189a62bf12
Closes-bug: #1396982

The code change itself is fine, I have several issues with the tests, i.e. I'm not sure why some things are being mocked out, there is quite a bit of copy/paste from what I can tell, etc.

Generally I like to see using mock for new tests, but I don't like seeing all of these existing tests using mox converted to mock, it makes this fairly straight-forward bug fix hard to review since not only do I need to make sure the quotas stuff is tested, but now I also have to make sure the newly re-written tests are still correct.

Not only that, but this is something we should backport to stable/juno (the bug was opened in the icehouse timeframe actually).  Backporting this fix with all of the mock conversion is going to be messy.

So can we just stick to updating the existing tests using mox, and then if you want to convert them to mock, do it on a follow-up dependent change?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-20 19:53:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

It sounds like this patch is trying to handle two issues:

* fix quota issues if a nova-compute restarts during a delete
* fix quota issues if a nova-compute restarts during a resize

Lets break this into two patches, one for each fix. It looks like fixing the delete should be easier -- maybe the right answer is to leave a hanging reservation that just expires in the end. By splitting this up it should be easier to and both of them.

I would like to see both of these cases fixed for Kilo (we are past K3 and getting ready to cut the RCs in a few weeks), since these are great examples of the types of bugs we should be focusing on right now.'}, {'account_id': 10795, 'date': '2015-03-31 11:38:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 20.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-31 13:01:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20: Verified+1

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-18 07:46:34.000000000', 'message': "Fix quota-update when nova-compute startup finish

Quotas was not getting updated when nova-compute startup finish
instance deletion, for the instances with task_state as 'deleting'.

When user sends request to delete an instance, its task_state gets
changed to 'deleting' state.
When an instance task_state is already in 'deleting' state and if
at that moment the rabbitmq-server get crashed by some reasons, then
the instance task_state remains in 'deleting' state and user
won't be able to delete the instance forever.

As of now, there is only one way to delete the instances, whose
task_state is 'deleting' state, by restarting the nova-compute
services where these instances are running.

After restarting the nova-compute service of the host, the instances
which were in deleting task_state gets deleted, but the quota for
those instances is not getting updated accordingly.

Added code to update the corresponding quota after deletion of
instances, for which task_state is 'deleting'.

Change-Id: Ida84d2d49d46540e0581dc3a58844c30bc1d2cff
Closes-Bug: 1296414

commit_message:
Fix quota-update of instances stuck in deleting when nova-compute startup finish

Quotas are not updated correctly for the instances whose task_state is
in deleting status during the nova-compute init_host call.

Added code to pass correct quota to the _delete_instance method.

Change-Id: Ida84d2d49d46540e0581dc3a58844c30bc1d2cff
Partial-Bug: 1296414

commit_message:
Do not remove subnet data on router delete, only remove when there are
no ports connected to that l2 subnet. Subnet class is needed even when
it is not connected to any router in order to install local subnet L3 traffic
offloading to Normal rule.

 Closes-Bug: #1462771

Change-Id: Ifb1da7bfaed438dd0b3424f72fa66dd70793da49

commit_message:
Add support for API microversions

This patch adds support in the REST API to accept a new
X-OpenStack-Magnum-API-Version header. This header is also returned
to clients as a hint to improve client response handling.

Additionally, new Minimum-Version and Maximum-Version headers
are also now returned, so as to inform clients of the supported range.

The requested version is stashed in the pecan.request.version object.

For reference as to why this approach was chosen, see the Nova spec on
microversioning:
http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/nova-specs/specs/kilo/approved/api-microversions.html
Ironic:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/150821

Implements: blueprint api-microversions
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/magnum/+spec/api-microversions

Co-Authored-By: ShaoHe Feng <shaohe.feng@intel.com>

Change-Id: I795f83cd829098e3d1f08d89ea33a8d986797d9f

commit_message:
Send 'security_groups_member_updated' when port changes

With ml2 plugin, when a port's IP or security group changes, it
should send 'security_groups_member_updated' message to other l2
agents which have same security group with this changed port.

Change-Id: I2e7622d2db4c173ac879a95a6e0adf92b858fe82
Closes-bug: #1448022

Fix container quota headers

Are all KMIP appliances guaranteed to support PKCS #1?

If different appliances only support different standards, then the number of configuration options could grow very quickly... Perhaps the transformation should be moved to a lower-level library like PyKMIP rather than Barbican?

Also, I personally dislike lots of if blocks for various global variables -- the complexity grows exponentially with the number of globals that interact with each other. If this change belongs in Barbican, perhaps the transformation to / from PKCS #1 belongs in a separate class rather than co-mingled with the basic KMIP secret store implementation? (This change could also be deferred til a later refactoring, but it might be easier in the long run to do it now rather than refactoring later.)'}, {'account_id': 6783, 'date': '2015-05-26 18:52:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

Joel, here are my responses to your comments.

"Are all KMIP appliances guaranteed to support PKCS #1?"
No, there are different KMIP profiles that a server can implement. Some only support symmetric keys, so those would obviously not support PKCS#1.

Now having said that I would expect almost all distributions that support asymmetric keys to support PKCS#8, which is why we chose that in the first place. I was surprised when it was not supported by a device, and if they do not support PKCS#8 or PKCS#1 then you are really in trouble. This is basically a fall back technique that says try PKCS#1. The only reason it is in use is because one of the devices we are testing does not support PKCS#8. I expect that to be fixed in the future, but until then I need something. Once that is implemented then we can remove this code.

"If different appliances only support different standards, then the number of configuration options could grow very quickly... Perhaps the transformation should be moved to a lower-level library like PyKMIP rather than Barbican?"

I do not expect another variable like this. This is really a one time deal because of a particular device. I do not anticipate other configuration options like this.

At the moment there is no place to put this in the PyKMIP code. The PyKMIP code is rather low-level and closely mirrors the spec. The spec says you must provide bytes and key format. I cannot think of a way to hide this in PyKMIP until a higher-level interface is created to store a generic private or public key.'}, {'account_id': 7789, 'date': '2015-05-28 17:36:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Added pkcs1_only Configuration to KMIP

Not all KMIP appliances support PKCS#8. Some only support PKCS#1. This
configuration option allows those KMIP appliances to still be used as
part of the KMIP secret store.

Change-Id: Ia65bf7c3699ca200a48906b647abc72686cab658

commit_message:
Renaming ACL creator-only to project-access flag

In vancouver summit, it was decided that 'project-access' flag is more
clear than 'creator-only' flag mentioned in spec. The renamed flag
more clearly reflects the intended behavior associated with this flag.

As part of this change, following changes have been.
Column renamed in secret_acls and container_acls tables.
Updated existing creator_only flag values as now project_access flag
is negation of existing flag value.

Updated model as now default project_access value is True.
Updated controller logic to reflect default change.
Updated policy to reflect expected flag value.

Modified all tests to reflect flag rename and expected reverse value.

Updated ACL docs to reflect flag rename

Change-Id: I67942ed3efb1918c04efaff7ce31156750cb4207

commit_message:
Return new secgroup object

The create method for a security group had a bug in that it was
not returning the newly created security group.

This also moves the logic for normalizing the nova data into the
_utils module since it is reused.

Change-Id: I19a3063769f1fc8c7bfd1d57aae0e5b839b8189c

commit_message:
Stop using function deprecated in Python 3

Python 3 deprecated the logger.warn method in favor of warning.

 DeprecationWarning: The 'warn' method is deprecated, use 'warning'
 instead

Change-Id: Idbd4de3c7c631fb2c235701c9b300c37a90d9538

commit_message:
Add NoOp dogpile cache backend

Add NoOp dogpile cache backend which will be the default cache
backend for heat. This cache backend does nothing so it allows
to prevent unintentional use of caching in heat.

More feature-rich back-ends will be added later.

Change-Id: I24fd8d01b983bb1ab90dac87154dc4002a1d76f2
Implements: constraint-validation-cache

commit_message:
Remove deprecated old attribute schema

This change is a part of changes discussed here:
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/YVR-heat-liberty-deprecation

- Removed deprecation warning
- Removed hook for old attribute schema
- Re-factored test for type property of attribute schema

commit_message:
Move manila resources in-tree

This change relocates the manila resources from the contrib area into the main
resource tree. It was originally added to contrib/ because of the project's
incubation status, and more specifically because the client is not in the
global-requirements.txt file. However, when this was discussed at the summit in
Vancouver, the decision was to move the resources to main tree but skip
registration if the client is not installed. This will save users from the
trouble of installing it as a plugin.

Change-Id: I9f43eba2abea351e1c5427b0968cbccab355992c

commit_message:
Call sudo with -H in pip_install

Commit 7aa7699acb764fd73322f8926eb5e967d71e25b0 was an incomplete
cherry pick since it missed the part that added -H to sudo pip install.

This is similar to what was added in change
If791b9b25d6a4280dab19117004184e57e78d038.

This is needed on stable/icehouse only since the change was made in
Kilo originally and backported to stable/juno.  This should fix grenade
against stable/juno changes where the 'old' side is stable/icehouse.

Change-Id: Ia52823ec2e322f78d407993010eb04adf39a242c
Closes-Bug: #1463149

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/00/181600/1/check/noop/7fbfa48/ : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 6525, 'date': '2015-05-11 05:11:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(4 comments)

Thanks for starting the BP, it effectively helps stepping back, which turns out to be really necessary as this stage as the openstacklib is such an crucial corner stone.

I think the 'workflow' needs to be crystal clear and relatively straightforward for anyone (providers and users) to implement and use. 

The Openstack configuration file can be defined as an interface, implemented as a Module, so providers can choose to use or not.

Rather than having a hash floating around containing the credentials data, it would be more robust to have a class encapsulating it. But hash or object, I don't think we have the need, ENV object is what we're dealing with, coming from default ENV, RC or sucked out of config file."}, {'account_id': 6525, 'date': '2015-05-11 05:13:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-11 05:13:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

LGTM, waiting for some other reads before +2.'}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2015-05-11 19:31:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

I started to make inline comments and then realized that I was confused about the purpose of the spec, so it's hard to comment on the specifics.

The introductory paragraph makes this statement:

> OpenStack, there is a need to consolidate and clearly define the authentication sources

This implies to me that this is a spec to better define the order of operations for the providers gathering credentials in the absence of the auth parameter. The spec doesn't clearly describe why the current solution is inadequate, though we had lengthy discussion about it on the mailing list and IRC.

Later the spec says:

> Having a common and standardized way to operate those files and the credentials information they contain is needed.

Which says that actually we are discussing how to manage the config values in the keystone_authtoken sections of the *.conf files. Then the spec makes no further mention of this issue.

I would like to see this spec have a more solid, verbose Problem Description section. Without that, it's hard to evaluate the proposed solution and API impacts."}, {'account_id': 9983, 'date': '2015-05-11 19:50:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

> The spec doesn't clearly describe why the current solution is inadequate, though we had lengthy discussion about it on the mailing list and IRC.

Would it be sufficient to summarize the mailing list and IRC discussion and put a link to the mailing list archives and IRC logs?"}, {'account_id': 9983, 'date': '2015-05-11 20:02:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Maybe "consolidation" is the wrong word.  What about "Provide flexible Keystone authentication with well-defined precedence for OpenStack Puppet modules"?'}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2015-05-11 21:10:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> Would it be sufficient to summarize the mailing list and IRC discussion and put a link to the mailing list archives and IRC logs?

Yes

> Maybe "consolidation" is the wrong word. What about "Provide flexible Keystone authentication with well-defined precedence for OpenStack Puppet modules"?

That sounds a little more descriptive. Also want to make it clear that this is about the API providers, not the config files (or make it clear that it's about both, if I'm misunderstanding).'}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2015-05-11 21:20:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

messages:
[{'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-06-09 02:09:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10206, 'date': '2015-06-09 02:13:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Hi Zane,
Thank you for submitting this patch. I think handling invalid type is not a solution. This is an issue in Kubernetes swagger spec. So we should correct it in Kubernetes.

I have submitted a patch for it https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186674/.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-06-09 02:14:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This appears to be an issue since forever, probably nobody has had to read any output with those fields filled in yet.

As an aside, I'm wondering what the value of Swagger is here when we only use 3 types and one of them isn't even valid."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-06-09 02:15:46.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Cool, I agree that's better"}]

commit_message:
Handle 'any' type in k8s client

The API definition for Kubernetes is full of the invalid Swagger type
"any". Add special handling for this case to swagger.py so that we can
work with actual Kubernetes output without crashing.

Change-Id: Ib4ee469c101448151af1632132617c83e1edfa81

commit_message:
horizon-policy-abstraction spec

remove from Kilo to Liberty

Abstract policy into "name", "object", "violation-condition", "action"
and "data", and express this abstraction in Horizon. This abstraction
is not just a expression of datasource drivers, and it makes those
users who are not familiar with Datalog express their intent more
easily and intuitively.

modified:   horizon-policy-abstraction.rst

-Clarify the meanings of abstraction elements and give some examples
-Give an example to show how the UI looks like and how to use it
-Illustrate the extention mechanism


Change-Id: I4c26bcb27f3f14cd2961a6ff642d2bcfbaccca79

commit_message:
Merge extended-volume functional tests of v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges extended-volume functional tests.

Change-Id: I18f3c9f3e3b253006b1a34b4739716aa21275d66

Neutron LBaaS data model allows the users to pick a specific
provider to implement a given load balancer instance (described
by Pool in LBaaS v1.0 API). This commit brings this option into
the heat resources as a property and an attribute.

commit_message:
neutron loadbalancer resource: provider property

Neutron LBaaS data model allows the users to pick a specific
provider to implement a given load balancer instance (described
by Pool in LBaaS v1.0 API). This commit brings this option into
the heat resources as a property and an attribute.

Co-Authored-By: Magesh GV <magesh.gv@oneconvergence.com>
Change-Id: Id55b8e615516c2ffd9d06980fb60707b207c356e

_delete(). And set the value of result['disableApiTermination']
to "False" in api/ec2/cloud.py._format_attr_disable_api_termination().

This patch uses the second method.

commit_message:
The instance property "disable_terminate" is not actually needed

The current instance object has a property named "disable_terminate"
but it is set to "False" when init instance object, and there are
no other method to modify this value.

It is then used twice, once in compute/api.py._delete(),
this parameter will be checked to see wheter the instance
can be terminated or not, if this parameter is "True", the
function will return directly. Since this parameter is
set to be "False" and there are no other way to modify it, this
check logic is actually useless.

Another usage of this parameter is in
api/ec2/cloud.py._format_attr_disable_api_termination(),
This parameter is passed to result['disableApiTermination'].

There can be two ways to fix this:
1. Add methods to modify this property in Create-instance,
Update-instance, etc. to make this parameter actually useful.

2. Delete this property and also the check logic in compute/api.py
_delete(). And set the value of result['disableApiTermination']
to "False" in api/ec2/cloud.py._format_attr_disable_api_termination().

This patch uses the second method.

Change-Id: Icb2a293025d1b501215f68ca7946af25daec9088
Closes-Bug:1454515

commit_message:
Switch USE_CLUSTER to USE_NEW_STACK

In devmido, USE_CLUSTER has been deprecated in favor of USE_NEW_STACK.
Update devstack plugin to do use the new variable.

Change-Id: Ib68ec6af333cd18edef11fa8100d0ac1524c16ae
Implements: MNP-136

commit_message:
Common base class for unit tests

A common base class is defined to provide a place to put fixtures
that affect all tests. For example, we could add a fixture that
ensures that no deprecated function was used.

Change-Id: Id024296de80f753aeabd6f418d459096fdb89838

commit_message:
Revert "Insert tenant_id validation for fw and fw-policy"

This reverts commit ac12fe19e2845a2459b70deaef85915ad450419c.

Reverted change wrongly assumes that tenant_id is always provided on
firewall create and update BUT tenant_id attribute is forbidden on
update and consequently breaks firewall-update.

Change-Id: I72bec28ed33dc4d7431a95f30cebf452acda5f3b
Closes-Bug: #1463066

commit_message:
Make logging option values configurable

It is not always desirable to log full set of conf at service
start. This change adds new option "log_options" that allows to
enable or disable logging values of all registered options.

Also moved list_opts function for service submodule to service.py
as service and eventlet_backdoor opts have to be grouped together
and changed the entrypoint accordingly.

Change-Id: I2a97ebf736fd361e6f1d05796d5077bc9627ff85
Closes-Bug: #1461250

commit_message:
Fix ignored E121 to E125 pep 8 rules

Fix pep8 violations for E121, E122, E123, E124, E125 and remove the
ignored rules from tox.ini.

E125 no longer should be ignored as the rule has been updated and shows
valid styling validation. Other style suggestions for writing long if
statements can be found here https://stackoverflow.com/questions/181530
if this rule violation causes any issue.

Closes-Bug: 1462955
Change-Id: Ic9a31a9dff15da634a97dfe9cdff6d367ecc17e9

commit_message:
Add l3-agent to process checks in neutron plugin

neutron-l3-agent is a critical neutron agent which needs to be
monitored.  This change adds that process check.

Change-Id: If5312505ac505e870119a03d4c63f56b85476ba1
Closes-bug: 1461267

commit_message:
Fix submit button not working in Angular Launch Instance modal

When 'Launch Instance' button is enabled, clicking on the button
doesn't do anything. This patch fixes the issue.

Change-Id: I4da2f81e89d343d7418091ddb92a461550bf0ed6
Closes-Bug: #1463163

commit_message:
Split slow rally job to several small ones

Previously scenarios were balanced between rally and rally-neutron jobs.
Here we move cinder, heat and nova scenraios in separate jobs. Some
scenarios are left in rally-neutron jobs just to check compatability.

Change-Id: If9bee6c70c5fdb830bc2f5691fe347f2167f23da

commit_message:
Add analysis routine for subpolicy construction

This change adds find_subpolicy to the Runtime engine, which analyzes
a given policy to carve out the subpolicy pertinent to the policy
language given to the function.  In this version of the code,
the policy language is described by a set of required tables that
must be relevant to the subpolicy, a set of prohibited tables that
may not be relevant to the subpolicy, and a set of output tables
that all rules must help define.

Change-Id: I0ed8f2035fc7026cfae39d1217659e1420a485ce

commit_message:
Add a new `ls_r` method

Instead of having a `ls` method that when used recursively
*always* returns the absolute path of items in the fake in
memory storage tree and *relative* paths (when used in
non-recursive mode) add a new `ls_r` method that can return
absolute *or* relative paths.

In the future it is highly likely that the the `ls` recursive
keyword argument will be removed (so preferring and
moving to the `ls_r` should occur earlier rather than
later), so this also adds a debtcollector removed keyword
argument decorator over the existing `ls` to ensure that users
are aware of this change (as well as a adjusted docstring).

Fixes bug 1458114

Change-Id: Id2a5869e94ac44679020a14297d1073d1dc2718f

commit_message:
Handle modals properly when disabling table actions

This fixes a problem when attempting to disable table actions on
a modal dialog. It causes the Launch Instance modal to render
incorrectly and other modals result in a
"$form.on is not a function" error displayed in the browser
console. This is because the modal init function is assuming the
argument passed in is a jQuery reference to the modal but in
reality it is just the modal DOM node itself. The problem is fixed
by making a jQuery reference to the modal before preparing to
disable the actions of any tables that might be displayed on it.

Closes-Bug: #1462544
Change-Id: I56399468ff5e2b5bcd0b285ece0d6dd001500c24

commit_message:
Decrease replication slave retry wait time

If the mysql replication slave fails to connect to the master on
its first attempt, it will wait 60 seconds to retry (60 seconds is
the mysql default). This is too long as the guest only waits 60
seconds to determine if the slave is running. It doesn't make sense
to increase the timeout as decreasing the connect retry time will
make the slave get into a the correct state faster. This change
decreases the retry time to 15 seconds which should be more than
enough time to possibly withstand 2 or 3 failures and still get
connected.

Change-Id: Ib53daca645ed05f26258ca6b309ab11b0384edd9
Closes-bug: 1462520

commit_message:
Don't emit volume tracebacks in inventory debug

It's ok if a cloud doesn't have volumes, and it's a question we can ask
of the cloud. Now, keystone tells us about it by way of throwing an
EndpointNotFound exception. But it's a normal logic exception, not a
"this is unexpected" exception. So we can handle it, log a sane error,
and move on, rather than logging the full traceback.

commit_message:
Ironic: Don't report resources for nodes without instances

Ironic falsely reports resources as consumed for certain states. Some
of these states are not associated with an instance, and the resource
tracker will notice that and "correct" the driver. This allows nodes
in CLEANING, etc. to be scheduled to.

Fix this by only reporting resources consumed when an instance UUID
is associated with the node. This association happens before the deploy
starts, and is removed after Nova sees tear down as complete, so it
should be safe to only look at the instance UUID for this. For any
"unavailable" state, report that there are zero resources available,
never allowing the node to be scheduled to.

Closes-Bug: #1462374
Change-Id: I48913f724a1bbe3711ea543a50b9ba096d5e95d7

commit_message:
Stop using function deprecated in py34

Python 3.4 has deprecated some functions:

LOG.warn:
 DeprecationWarning: The 'warn' method is deprecated, use 'warning'
 instead

SafeConfigParser:
 DeprecationWarning: The SafeConfigParser class has been renamed to
 ConfigParser in Python 3.2. This alias will be removed in future
 versions. Use ConfigParser directly instead.

ConfigParser's readfp:
 DeprecationWarning: This method will be removed in future versions.
 Use 'parser.read_file()' instead.

Change-Id: I82829e05682931128eb6fcaf0c5e215671d1173d

commit_message:
Not use the deprecated argument

`project` argument is deprecated in keystoneclient for V3 API,
and use `default_project` instead, should use `default_project`
as the argument name in the openstackclient accordingly.

Change-Id: Ib9d70801c933a184afcdab75204393efa764fa87
Closes-Bug: #1462389

commit_message:
Scenario test to create and delete cluster

- Creates a nova instance and cue cluster
- Ssh into the nova instance and runs a test script to authenticate rabbitmq credentials
- Cleans up the nova instance, cue cluster and network

Implements: blueprint rally-scenario-tests
Change-Id: I610cebb6603f008e089599581eca9611f26cf80c

will cause "ignored explicit argument u'True'" error.

Change-Id: I49a033fd2821100283e217225896fc93a927edd2
(cherry picked from commit b29ee6f706bf7371f69b831f99727396ddb77cad)

commit_message:
Fix neutron_network for --router:external setting

Neutron can't be called with --router:external=True as that
will cause "ignored explicit argument u'True'" error.

Change-Id: I49a033fd2821100283e217225896fc93a927edd2
(cherry picked from commit b29ee6f706bf7371f69b831f99727396ddb77cad)

commit_message:
Unescape value in parse_allocation_pool

Neutron changed the library for formating shell output and it's now escaped. We
just make sure we'll unescape it before applying regexp.

Change-Id: I8250353bb8afb3e9431a0fe225e62b1c34f74924
(cherry picked from commit 659e2cb2d830fe4dd8888c734ad0170d0b22a549)

[{'created': '2015-06-01 23:31:58.000000000', 'message': "Fix ipv6 support

There is issue with ipv6 where address has to be in brackets, this causes the
underlying ruby TCPSocket to fail. Net::HTTP.new will fail without brackets on
joining the ipv6 address with :port or passing brackets to TCPSocket. It was
found that if we use Net::HTTP.start with url.hostname the incriminated code
won't be hit.

Change-Id: I99bbb8b7aaeae8958f757772ba6186f1e48a6778
Closes-Bug: rhbz#1185652
(cherry picked from commit c852fcdec66bfb894f3980685fece07ec3b6917c)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix ipv6 support

There is issue with ipv6 where address has to be in brackets, this causes the
underlying ruby TCPSocket to fail. Net::HTTP.new will fail without brackets on
joining the ipv6 address with :port or passing brackets to TCPSocket. It was
found that if we use Net::HTTP.start with url.hostname the incriminated code
won't be hit.

Change-Id: I99bbb8b7aaeae8958f757772ba6186f1e48a6778
Closes-Bug: rhbz#1185652
(cherry picked from commit c852fcdec66bfb894f3980685fece07ec3b6917c)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-01 23:34:26.000000000', 'message': 'stop puppet from breaking neutron

The neutron-ovs-cleanup service is meant to run at boot to tear down ovs
interfaces created by Neutron.  The service exits right after start when
cleaning up ovs bridges, which means that from Puppet's perspective it
is always "stopped".

By setting `ensure => started` on the neutron-ovs-cleanup service,
puppet was starting this service every time it runs, which would
completely disable Neutron networking.

This patch removes the `ensure` setting, such that the service will be
enabled and will run at boot but will not be erroneously started by
Puppet.

Change-Id: I623a3a0b672e00ddb8513cc346cbbfeca8fdf88b
(cherry picked from commit 824fed5fb274c412dd0e37b1337f24055b3b2b9d)
'}]
commit_message:
stop puppet from breaking neutron

The neutron-ovs-cleanup service is meant to run at boot to tear down ovs
interfaces created by Neutron.  The service exits right after start when
cleaning up ovs bridges, which means that from Puppet's perspective it
is always "stopped".

By setting `ensure => started` on the neutron-ovs-cleanup service,
puppet was starting this service every time it runs, which would
completely disable Neutron networking.

This patch removes the `ensure` setting, such that the service will be
enabled and will run at boot but will not be erroneously started by
Puppet.

Change-Id: I623a3a0b672e00ddb8513cc346cbbfeca8fdf88b
(cherry picked from commit 824fed5fb274c412dd0e37b1337f24055b3b2b9d)

commit_message:
Raise puppet error, if N-API anavail

W/o this change, empty lists could be returned
and broke puppet apply execution when Neutron
(or Keystone) API is anavail.

The solution is to raise Puppet error, if
returned lists are empty

Closes-bug: #1384101

Change-Id: I10b6592f709603043e97304366c54e53703939ea
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit 919a1016b28880b1dd295a0654987160f7776588)

[{'created': '2015-06-01 23:25:06.000000000', 'message': 'Corrects "ip link set" command

neutron_l3_ovs_bridge/neutron.rb executes the command
ip link set @resource[:name] up

This command fails when the resource name is “br” with the following error:
ip link set br up
"up" is invalid lladdr.

To correct this error execute with “ip link set dev @resource[:name] up”:

from ip link help:
ip link set { dev DEVICE | group DEVGROUP } [ { up | down }

Change-Id: I35b5ee79b05c01d4261935a55c8b3b86a7c8d8b2
(cherry picked from commit 45e05dd4b827bc6b442b35f82492f631168556ee)
'}]
commit_message:
Corrects "ip link set" command

neutron_l3_ovs_bridge/neutron.rb executes the command
ip link set @resource[:name] up

This command fails when the resource name is “br” with the following error:
ip link set br up
"up" is invalid lladdr.

To correct this error execute with “ip link set dev @resource[:name] up”:

from ip link help:
ip link set { dev DEVICE | group DEVGROUP } [ { up | down }

Change-Id: I35b5ee79b05c01d4261935a55c8b3b86a7c8d8b2
(cherry picked from commit 45e05dd4b827bc6b442b35f82492f631168556ee)

The display-name option for mod_wsgi's WSGIDaemonProcess directive
allows for a useful name to be used for the process command name.
This is generally useful, as it allows one to distinguish the
keystone wsgi processes from other httpd processes on the system in
the output of ps and similar commands.

This patch uses display names of 'keystone-main' and 'keystone-admin'
for the main and admin processes respectively.

Change-Id: Id79c3a36b3f84938070f41c7171dfee20d1745e9
Closes-bug: #1409119

commit_message:
Set WSGI process display-name

The display-name option for mod_wsgi's WSGIDaemonProcess directive
allows for a useful name to be used for the process command name.
This is generally useful, as it allows one to distinguish the
keystone wsgi processes from other httpd processes on the system in
the output of ps and similar commands.

This patch uses display names of 'keystone-main' and 'keystone-admin'
for the main and admin processes respectively.

Change-Id: Id79c3a36b3f84938070f41c7171dfee20d1745e9
Closes-bug: #1409119
(cherry picked from commit 7108a6e64f8e3c2c7586ce74b6af686dc16c6a28)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-01 20:54:47.000000000', 'message': "Fix catalog compilation when not configuring endpoint

Previously when you set $configure_endpoint to false and did not have a
keystone_endpoint resource with the same name as is defined by
glance::keystone::auth, the catalog would not be compiled. This was
because a relationship was being established where one resource in the
relationship didn't exist.

This changes this so that the relationship involving the Keystone
endpoint is only defined if $configure_endpoint is set to true.

Also, the test for when $configure_endpoint is false was set to check
for an endpoint that doesn't get created even if $configure_endpoint is
true. Fixed so that it checks for an endpoint that has the correct name
(the same as when using the default values to call the class).

Change-Id: I6631a656a888d0df7ab173705bea0598bd2b2f58
Closes-Bug: 1368686
(cherry-picked from commit ee0549f15dd6b9442b559ca363b934b60588b7e2)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix catalog compilation when not configuring endpoint

Previously when you set $configure_endpoint to false and did not have a
keystone_endpoint resource with the same name as is defined by
glance::keystone::auth, the catalog would not be compiled. This was
because a relationship was being established where one resource in the
relationship didn't exist.

This changes this so that the relationship involving the Keystone
endpoint is only defined if $configure_endpoint is set to true.

Also, the test for when $configure_endpoint is false was set to check
for an endpoint that doesn't get created even if $configure_endpoint is
true. Fixed so that it checks for an endpoint that has the correct name
(the same as when using the default values to call the class).

Change-Id: I6631a656a888d0df7ab173705bea0598bd2b2f58
Closes-Bug: 1368686
(cherry-picked from commit ee0549f15dd6b9442b559ca363b934b60588b7e2)

commit_message:
Command parameter to sync the correct Database

Without the correct --config-file parameter the glance-manage db_sync
command does not sync the correct database. The default without any
configuration is to use an SQLite Database at /var/lib/glance/glancedb.
This is most probably not what's intended.

Change-Id: I61f4e47ad082b48ee83b17df70e9856f640083b1
(cherry picked from commit c51c22770d2f371d7135300378e7bc14eb3fa193)

commit_message:
Create a sync_db boolean for Glance.

Other components offer the option to decide whether or not to run the db sync
command. Glance was missing this feature. This commit add this feature for
Glance.

Change-Id: Iec31d724370a40aee56ead5839ef47ceacf7223d
(cherry-picked from commit ab054853e18da72cc2eeb544d67eef743e389b5c)

commit_message:
Begin the transition to an explicit object registry

In oslo.versionedobjects, the registry is opt-in instead of implicit.
This patch sets the stage for moving to that by defining a no-op
registry with a compatible register method so that we can go ahead and
decorate the object classes and then move the registry underneath them.

Related to blueprint use-oslo-objects

Change-Id: Iddc68a2d8a9b103621bc60a7426fe495edf80aad

commit_message:
Correctly munge glance_image is_public property

glance expects True/False values whereas this type uses Yes/No.

Without this patch, puppet would return the following message with an
existing glance image with is_public attribute already set to 'True'.

puppet-agent[18190]: (/Stage[main]/Site::Controller/Glance_image[raring-server-cloudimg-amd64]/is_public) is_public changed 'True' to 'Yes'

Change-Id: I532e08e6815a8b03f5eb6a9495d886b9855762c8
(cherry picked from commit 031609b57284cf13877ce727c2e4672831a3dbe2)

commit_message:
Add inventory command to shade

The ansible inventory plugin is actually really useful for general
purpose debugging of cloud metadata. Also, having this in tree means we
can test it and make sure we don't break the interface for people.

Change-Id: Ibb1463936fac9a7e959e291a3856c4f8d32898e0

commit_message:

commit_message:
Unpin beaker-rspec

The latest version of beaker tries to manage sshd_config[1] in order to
pass through environment variables. JJB also tries to manage
sshd_config by adding Match blocks to securely allow root SSH[2]. When
beaker tries to append the PermitUserEnvironment line after the Match
blocks, SSH fails to open port 22 and beaker can't SSH in to the
node[3]. This patch unpins beaker-rspec and adds set_env: false to the
nodepool nodesets so that the set_env method is never called and does
not try to mess with the sshd_config.

[1] https://github.com/puppetlabs/beaker/blob/master/lib/beaker/host_prebuilt_steps.rb#L528
[2] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/project-config/tree/jenkins/jobs/puppet-module-jobs.yaml#n42
[3] http://logs.openstack.org/61/185161/1/check/gate-puppet-nova-puppet-beaker-rspec-dsvm-centos7/cd81608/console.html.gz#_2015-05-22_22_05_46_933
[4] https://github.com/puppetlabs/beaker/blob/master/lib/beaker/host_prebuilt_steps.rb#L502

Depends-on: Iefdf96325e11b470e864d5386a3eab0eb655c960
Change-Id: Ic5e44397df5558bb296646b666373ee1dc2343b0

commit_message:
Unpin beaker-rspec

The latest version of beaker tries to manage sshd_config[1] in order to
pass through environment variables. JJB also tries to manage
sshd_config by adding Match blocks to securely allow root SSH[2]. When
beaker tries to append the PermitUserEnvironment line after the Match
blocks, SSH fails to open port 22 and beaker can't SSH in to the
node[3]. This patch unpins beaker-rspec and adds set_env: false to the
nodepool nodesets so that the set_env method is never called and does
not try to mess with the sshd_config.

[1] https://github.com/puppetlabs/beaker/blob/master/lib/beaker/host_prebuilt_steps.rb#L528
[2] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/project-config/tree/jenkins/jobs/puppet-module-jobs.yaml#n42
[3] http://logs.openstack.org/61/185161/1/check/gate-puppet-nova-puppet-beaker-rspec-dsvm-centos7/cd81608/console.html.gz#_2015-05-22_22_05_46_933
[4] https://github.com/puppetlabs/beaker/blob/master/lib/beaker/host_prebuilt_steps.rb#L502

Change-Id: I48426b705732de9c310664fe7d1f5e6da82a0a5c

commit_message:
Unpin beaker-rspec

The latest version of beaker tries to manage sshd_config[1] in order to
pass through environment variables. JJB also tries to manage
sshd_config by adding Match blocks to securely allow root SSH[2]. When
beaker tries to append the PermitUserEnvironment line after the Match
blocks, SSH fails to open port 22 and beaker can't SSH in to the

nodepool nodesets so that the set_env method is never called and does
not try to mess with the sshd_config.

[1] https://github.com/puppetlabs/beaker/blob/master/lib/beaker/host_prebuilt_steps.rb#L528

commit_message:
Unpin beaker-rspec

The latest version of beaker tries to manage sshd_config[1] in order to
pass through environment variables. JJB also tries to manage
sshd_config by adding Match blocks to securely allow root SSH[2]. When
beaker tries to append the PermitUserEnvironment line after the Match
blocks, SSH fails to open port 22 and beaker can't SSH in to the
node[3]. This patch unpins beaker-rspec and adds set_env: false to the
nodepool nodesets so that the set_env method is never called and does
not try to mess with the sshd_config.

[1] https://github.com/puppetlabs/beaker/blob/master/lib/beaker/host_prebuilt_steps.rb#L528
[2] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/project-config/tree/jenkins/jobs/puppet-module-jobs.yaml#n42
[3] http://logs.openstack.org/61/185161/1/check/gate-puppet-nova-puppet-beaker-rspec-dsvm-centos7/cd81608/console.html.gz#_2015-05-22_22_05_46_933
[4] https://github.com/puppetlabs/beaker/blob/master/lib/beaker/host_prebuilt_steps.rb#L502
